This paper deals with the design of medium access control (MAC) protocols for wireless networks, which is a topic that falls under the category of networked systems (cs.NI). The paper also discusses the use of statistical tests to detect deviations from prescribed behavior, which is a topic that falls under the category of information theory (cs.IT). Additionally, the paper addresses the issue of selfish nodes manipulating protocols, which is a topic that falls under the category of computer security and cryptography (cs.CR). The paper proposes a review strategy for detecting deviations, which involves collecting signals from other nodes, and this is a topic that falls under the category of control systems (cs.SY). Finally, the paper provides analytical and numerical results to demonstrate the properties of the proposed protocols, which is a topic that falls under the category of distributed, parallel, and cluster computing (cs.DC).
